    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1986-07-09T08:39:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1986-07-09T08:39:00-05:00" n="121"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                <head>121. Electronic Message From <persName corresp="#p_RPW_1">Peter
                        Rodman</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to <persName
                        corresp="#p_LR_2">Robert Linhard</persName> of the National Security Council
                        Staff<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d121fn1">Source: National Archives,
                            <gloss target="#t_PROFS_1">PROFS</gloss> system, <persName
                            corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> Administration, ID 28677. Secret.
                        Copies were sent to <persName corresp="#p_MDR_1">McDaniel</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_MJF_1">Matlock</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SS_1">Sestanovich</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KS_1"
                            >Kraemer</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_MD_1">Mahley</persName>.
                        No minutes of the breakfast meeting were found.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1986-07-09T09:39:00-04:00">July 9, 1986, 9:39 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_SWP_1">S-W-P</gloss> Breakfast: <gloss target="#t_SDIO_1"
                            >SDIO</gloss> Study of <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                        Treaty</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_WJC_1">Whitehead</persName> raised this subject,
                    complaining that <persName corresp="#p_PRN_1">Perle</persName> was not allowing
                    anyone at State to see any of the results or progress of <gloss
                        target="#t_SDIO_1">SDIO</gloss>’s study of the effects of the restrictive
                    vs. broader interpretation of the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss> Treaty.
                    (The Admiral noted that this was a study he had asked for.) <persName
                        corresp="#p_TWHIV_1">Will Taft</persName> replied that so far it’s only a
                    preliminary study; Cap got a preliminary briefing in March and sent it back for
                    more work; no results would be in until next month. <persName corresp="#p_WJC_1"
                        >Whitehead</persName> said fine; could they have an interim briefing? Ikle
                    noted that the study had been treated as very close-hold because of the danger
                    of leaks.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_TWHIV_1">Taft</persName> said he would “take the question”
                    and get back to them.</p>
                <p>On the substance, Ikle said the study was likely to come to the common-sense
                    conclusions that under the restrictive interpretation we would bump up against
                    the limits earlier and have less information on which to base a deployment
                    decision. The Admiral noted that the main difference had to do with the
                    possibilities for integrated testing of systems.</p>
            </div>
